  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">WASH response to COVID-19 Pandemic in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to address critical lifesaving WASH services and supplies needs of 77,000 returnees, people displaced in formal/informal Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) sites and Informal settlements on the fringes of urban areas in 19 high risk districts identified by the Government of Afghanistan&#x2019;s multi-sector response plan for the COVID-19 pandemic. The programme target area was identified and established based on the recent IOM-led Displacement Tracking Matrix (DTM) report and OCHA update report on Population Movements (January to December 2019). UNICEF will target up to 19 districts (in 10 provinces) among the 41 recommended by the WASH Cluster for the COVID-19 response, while also having continuous consultations with the Ministry of Public Health (MoPH) and WHO on the dynamic nature of disease transmission, and making the necessary and relevant adjustments to the WASH preventive response as needed.


The proposed action will promote healthy hygienic behavior through the effective use of critical WASH services and supplies. It will target returnees from Iran and Pakistan and displaced families, especially young children, women, girls, boys, the elderly and the disabled living in the IDP camps as well as informal sites and urban slums in up to 19 high risk districts. Since there are many IDPs settled in host communities and they are also in a continuous move to find the most appropriate and secure areas for their settlement, the exact number of IDPs living in host communities is constantly changing. For this reason, UNICEF will undertake a quick assessment of population numbers and site selection in close consultation with concerned government ministries and local authorities. UNICEF, as the agency of last resort for the provision of WASH services, will coordinate the response efforts, and avoid any chance of duplication to ensure an effective and efficient use the scarce resources allocated for the COVID-19 response.


This proposal is based on the WASH cluster strategy note for AHF 2nd Reserve Allocation (RA) 2020 and allocation strategy for Afghanistan and is in accordance with the national WASH cluster strategy, targets and priorities for the revised Afghanistan 2018-2021 Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP).</narrative>
  </description>
